caption: Decided to visit Glassey after seeing an ad for it on social media (FB or IG.) Seemed nice based on the photos.  Parked out front, the place looks just as it had in the photos online. We walked up the stairs (party of 2), and began feeling a sense of "this place seems cool."  We were the second party in the store at the time. One other young couple already sitting in the corner.  No one at the register. Saw a lady working in the kitchen.  "Oh well, we will wait."  The lady in the kitchen definitely saw us, it is one with an open view. She did not acknowledge us, or greet us while we waited by the register.  "Someone will be here shortly", I thought.  A young lady came to the register after a few minutes. Seemed like she was doing something upstairs (I didn't ask, not my business.)  She told us to take a look over the menu, and that she would be with us shortly to take our orders.  Told us that there was a hookah lounge upstairs as well, and that if we wanted hookah we could order it and then sit upstairs. She walked away.  About ten minutes went by again. No worry.  The same young lady came by after what seemed like a good eight or nine minutes, took our order. Glassey is a place at which you order at the register and pay before taking a seat. Ballin.  Ordered the Chicken Biryani , Chicken Tikka Burger, Channa Masala Sabzi, two samosas, two mimosas. $69.58 bucks.  We sat down, saw our drinks being made, and then saw a sign explaining to us that guests are to bus their own tables. Sure.  Eight or nine minutes go by - the young lady brought us our two samosas. We got started. Samosas are nothing complicated, and they were good.  Ten minutes go by. Another ten. Another ten. Maybe even another.  The same young lady who had taken our order and prepared our drinks came by and let us know that the Chicken Biryani was unavailable, and that we could substitute it for something else.  We asked that our order for chicken biryani be substituted for for a butter chicken dish.  Not my personality to be an irritable guest, so I did not ask about our other food. The young lady helping us did not bring it up. Nice.  We ordered two more mimosas, continued to wait, drinking our mimosas, and enjoyed the dance-inspired Indian-film music remixes playing on the TVs above the bar.  Our food arrived. The burger was delicious. No argument there. Happy to have ordered it. Channa masal sabzi was sub par. Not happy to have ordered it. Butter chicken  was sub-par. Not happy to have ordered it.  We got through our meal, laughing inside about what just happened to us, thinking about the potential of this place, how we had a not so savory experience, and how we spent so much time there. Awkward.  The host asked us what we thought of the food. We communicated to her, clear and earnest compliments for the taste of the chicken tikka burger.  We got up and paid the rest of the bill (four additional mimosas). Total came to $29.10 .  Summary: 100 ish bucks for:  1) One really delicious burger 2) Two decent samosas, 3) One order of ok at best, Butter chicken (we couldn't try the biryani because we were told that it was unavailable after over half an hour of being there) 4) Six mimosas 5) Way too much time in the place  Left the place feeling as though we were not really welcomed, which was a disappointment because the decor is nice, and the food is decent (albeit overpriced.)  Thought I'd give it a bit of time before writing a review. Did a little googling, came to find out that the young lady helping us was the owner, and has been featured in a few local publications as a young entrepreneur / restaurant owner.  That's cool. Something to be proud of. She must be proud :)  Before writing this review, I read a few others - seems like many other folks have had a similar experience here.  Might go there again for a drink if I'm in the area, and have time to wait an  hour for the chicken tikka burger.
Great service, really nice people, food was fantastic. Highly recommend the masala fries!
Great food, prices and drinks. Really cool atmosphere! It’s a family affair so it’s really comforting and the owner is so friendly highly recommend!

I wish I can rate this place with 0 star. They make us wait for more than 1 hour to deliver our food and they claimed that they are going to prepare it after we ask for a refund. Really bad customer service.
Food was great,  try the Chicken tikka burger and samosas.   Friendly Owners and a nice local place. Best tiktoc find yet.
Best place in the area ! Great business !! Food drinks everything amazing !!!
Delicious and traditional indian street food. Hidden gem that I'll definitely go back to!

The worst place to go. The service is really bad. There is no one at the register to take the order. I was waiting at the register for 10-15 minutes before someone came to take the order at the register. They ran out of food way before closing. It took them 45 minutes to realize that they ran out of food we ordered. It took them 45 to bring the drinks. I will never go there and won't advice yiu to go there unless you have a lot to time to waste just waiting for the food and drinks to come. That to if they have the food you ordered and they realize to let you know before hand if they don't have food.

Just left this place.  2 stars for the mom who was working her butt off in the kitchen making food.  The food is ok but the stand out items are definitely the fries and burgers.  The 2 star rating is coming from being there for 2 hours and not being given any food. We had to take the food to go because we were at a point where we had to leave and they had just wrapped up our food. Spent most of the time drinking. Although the young bartender/waitress/owner was nice in accommodating things that were on the menu but not available when we ordered, the drinks are WAY overpriced.  Typical Indian place, charge $15-$17 for a drink that is made with well alcohol and barely any of it.  We ordered around $200 worth of food and about $150 with of liquor.  None of it worth it.  Not worth going here in my opinion but nice try!  Get better operations, have a better attitude, and step it up a bit and I think you guys have a chance to make it. Otherwise, you won’t last.
Great food
The samosas are amazing. Very homemade and fresh!

*COVID REVIEW*  Love Glassey! Their use of spices is authentically Indian while their dishes have fun hints of fusion cuisine in a way I've rarely seen. Their portions are generous and well packaged for pick up / delivery during COVID. It's cool to know their owner is DC's youngest restaurant owner as well!
The restaurant employees were not full wearing masks and the food took about an hour

People with wheelchairs and strollers be warned - it is very difficult to get up the stairs.  The food is alright - the best item on the menu is the chicken tikka burger. There is nothing special about the butter chicken - very bland.
Overpriced, average taste and undercooked roti

I was very excited to try this place, but it disappointed. Firstly it toke 45 minutes for me to receive my food. I’m not kidding 45 minutes, I know cause the receipt has the time stamp of when I ordered. Keep in mind it was only me and another customer, on a Saturday. Also no explanation from the staff of why it toke so long.  With that being said, the food is good. The masala fries are very flavorful. The chicken tikka burger was good, chicken was a bit dry. It’s worth noting that the chicken burger with fries costs you a cool $21. So do with that information what you will.  The Jiya’s curry was good, not great. I did like the inclusion of chickpeas. Overall not the best experience and I likely won’t be returning, but if you do find yourself here definitely try the masala fries!
We had the Chicken Tikka Burger and Mango lassi. They were both great and flavorful!! The chicken was a bit dry but overall really good

We were in the neighborhood on a weekday and decided to get some takeout from Glassey. This restaurant had been on our list for a while ever since we got to try food from this restaurant at our friends'.  The location is convenient though you have to look for the entrance next to the other businesses.  We tried the following dishes: Chicken Biryani  - this was a good dish - rice was cooked well and the chicken was tender and flavorful.  Saag Chicken - this was a good dish and had a kick to it too. The spinach provided a nice flavor to the dish.  Butter Chicken - it was a good dish, not necessarily what you would expect for the traditional butter chicken. But it had enough flavors to be a good dish.  The accompanying channa dish with the rice was a good version that satisfy all types of palates.  Definitely a good place for Indian food and we should be back soon for more of their food!
Food is unreal!

The food is AMAZING! I would definitely recommend this place and can’t wait to eat here again. I had the Jiya’s Tiffin Paneer which had the perfect amount of spice. We also shared the crabby fries that I would recommend everyone try!

I had the tikki burger with crabby fries. It honestly was super disappointing. The burger had barely any flavor and was wayy overpriced. The fries were a soggy mess. I paid $6-7 for the side of fries and got less than a handful of soggy fries. You can easily eat Indian food elsewhere for cheaper.

Loved their chicken tikka burger. The fried onions in burger added a different taste to it. Masala fries were the best of all. Overall the taste was good, all the recipes were new. Cons- it’s a very small restaurant. Would prefer takeout than dine in.

I didn't get to add a picture because I ate the food so fast, but I had the Butter Chicken meal. It was definitely was the best Indian dish I've had in the DC area. The staff was very helpful in answering questions and providing suggestions regarding the dishes as I am not an expert in traditional Indian cuisine. Everyone had masks on and there was sanitizer readily available throughout the restaurant. They also have a nice patio area that keeps you covered from all of the elements with ample seating. I will most definitely be returning to try the Masala Fries and much more.

WOW. This may be my first restaurant review ever, I'm not sure. But. Tonight I had dinner from Glassey and it was AMAZING. Incredible. I tried the Bangin' Bartha Sabzi, the Palak Paneer Sabzi, the samosas, and the Chicken Karahi Curry. Every one of them was fantastic and delicious.  I will say, it turned out to be quite spicy—which I really liked, but if you do not like spicy food you should tell them.  I got takeout, but they also had what looked like 6-8 outdoor tables.  I had learned of this restaurant before it opened, but did not manage to try it until now. I am ABSOLUTELY going back.
Great food and incredibly friendly staff! The masala fries were definitely our favorite item
Enjoyed the Chicken Karahi Curry and Butter Paneer.
Like the kathi rolls both  paneer and chicken .We have not tried other items yet.
Everything I got was fantastic -- can't wait to try more!

This meal was disappointing. We got the palak paneer, butter chicken, garlic naan, paneer paratha, and the masala fries. The Masala fries were nothing like the picture and were a soggy mess. The butter chicken proportion was nothing like the pictures and just tasted like cream. The palak paneer was the worst made with poor quality paneer and had absolutely no flavor. Will not be ordering from here again.
So so delicious!! Really reasonably priced for the quality and the portions. Definitely a new favorite!!
